05447nam a22008655i 9780812200317DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112005pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122003177 a10.9783/97808122003172doi  a(DE-B1597)448889  a(OCoLC)979630680  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHV640.5.P36bP48 2005eb 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a362.87/089/9274056922221 aPeteet, Julie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLandscape of Hope and Despair :bPalestinian Refugee Camps /cJulie Peteet. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b18 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Ethnography of Political Violence00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter One. Introduction: Palestinian Refugees -- tChapter Two. Prelude to Displacement: Producing and Enacting Knowledge -- tChapter Three. Aid and the Construction of the Refugee -- tChapter Four. Producing Place, Spatializing Identity, 1948–68 -- tChapter 5. Landscape of Hope and Despair -- tChapter Six. The Geography of Terror and Reconfinement -- tConclusion: Refugee Camps and the Wall -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNearly half of the world's eight million Palestinians are registered refugees, having faced partition and exile. Landscape of Hope and Despair examines this refugee experience in Lebanon through the medium of spatial practices and identity, set against the backdrop of prolonged violence. Julie Peteet explores how Palestinians have dealt with their experience as refugees by focusing attention on how a distinctive Palestinian identity has emerged from and been informed by fifty years of refugee history. Concentrating ethnographic scrutiny on a site-specific experience allows the author to shed light on the mutually constitutive character of place and cultural identification.Palestinian refugee camps are contradictory places: sites of grim despair but also of hope and creativity. Within these cramped spaces, refugees have crafted new worlds of meaning and visions of the possible in politics. In the process, their historical predicament was a point of departure for social action and thus became radically transformed. Beginning with the calamity of 1948, Landscape of Hope and Despair traces the dialectic of place and cultural identification through the initial despair of the 1950s and early 1960s to the tumultuous days of the resistance and the violence of the Lebanese civil war and its aftermath. Most significantly, this study invokes space, place, and identity to construct an alternative to the received national narratives of Palestinian society and history.The moving stories told here form a larger picture of these refugees as a people struggling to recreate their sense of place and identity and add meaning to their surroundings through the use of culture and memory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPalestinian ArabszLebanonxEconomic conditions. 0aPalestinian ArabszLebanonxSocial conditions. 0aRefugee campszLebanon. 4aHuman Rights. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican Studies.  aAnthropology.  aAsian Studies.  aFolklore.  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aLinguistics.  aMiddle Eastern Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Social Sciencesz978311041361808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/97808